{{refimprove|date=October 2017}} The '''problem of the creator of God''' is the controversy regarding the hypothetical [[Causality|cause]] responsible for the [[existence of God]], presuming God exists. A common challenge to [[theism|theistic]] propositions of a [[creator deity]] as a necessary [[first cause|first-cause]] explanation for the [[universe]] is the question: "Who created God?".<ref>''The God Book'', [[Michael Arnheim]], 2015, p. 18.</ref> It contests the proposition that the universe cannot exist without a creator by asserting that the creator of the universe must have the same restrictions. This, in turn, may lead to a problem of [[infinite regress]] wherein each newly presumed creator of a creator is itself presumed to have its own creator.
Some faith traditions have such an element as part of their doctrine. [[Jainism and non-creationism|Jainism]] posits that the universe is eternal and has always existed. In [[Mormonism]] it is believed that the God of this Earth was once a mortal human, who had a father of his own. [[Ismailism]] rejects the idea of God as the ''first cause'', due to the doctrine of God's incomparability and source of any existence including [[Abstract and concrete|abstract objects]].<ref>Arzina R. Lalani Degrees of Excellence: A Fatimid Treatise on Leadership in Islam I.B.Tauris 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-857-71202-8}} page 3</ref>
==Perspectives== [[Rajneesh|Osho]] writes: {{quote|No, don't ask that. That's what all the religions say — don't ask who created God. But this is strange — why not? If the question is valid about existence, why does it become invalid when it is applied to God? And once you ask who created God, you are falling into a regress absurdum.<ref>''The God Conspiracy: The Path from Superstition to Super Consciousness'', [[Rajneesh|Osho]], 2010.</ref>}}
John Humphreys writes: {{quote|... if someone were able to provide the explanation, we would be forced to embark upon what philosophers call an infinite regress. Having established who created God, we would then have to answer the question of who created God's creator.<ref>''In God We Doubt'', John Humphrys, 2008. {{isbn|978-0340976739}}</ref>}}
In ''The God Book'', Deist [[Michael Arnheim]] writes: {{quote|The atheist objection is that if God created the universe, who created God? Judging by the number of times that [[Richard Dawkins|Dawkins]] repeats this same point in ''[[The God Delusion]]'', one must assume that he sees this as a killer argument against the existence of God.<ref>''The God Book'', [[Michael Arnheim]], 2015, p. 18.</ref>}}
Alan Lurie writes: {{quote|If God created the Universe, who created God? That is a dilemma that religious folks desperately try to avoid.” The question, “Who created God?”, has been pondered by theologians for millennia, and the answer is both surprisingly obvious and philosophically subtle...
...whatever one thinks about the beginnings of the Universe, there is “something” at the very origin that was not created. This is an inescapable given a cosmic truth.<ref>Alan Lurie, ''The Rabbi Who Believes in Zeus: Popular Myths About Religion, Faith, and God'', 2013</ref>}}
==Responses== Defenders of religion have countered that the question is improper:
{{quote|We ask, “If all things have a creator, then who created God?” Actually, only created things have a creator, so it's improper to lump God with his creation. God has revealed himself to us in the Bible as having always existed.<ref>Steve Husting, ''Doubt Busters'', 2017, p. 20. {{isbn|1387312820}}.</ref>}}
It is also argued that the question becomes irrelevant if the Universe is presumed to have circular time instead of linear time.<ref>Paul Gabler, ''Slices of a Life'', 2015, Ch. 30 {{isbn|1504960645}}.</ref>
